import java.io.*;
import java.net.*;

public class TelnetClient {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        String server = "localhost";
        int port = 23;
        try {
            TelnetClient telnet = new TelnetClient();
            telnet.connect(server, port);
            InputStream in = telnet.getInputStream();
            OutputStream out = telnet.getOutputStream();
            out.write("ls\n".getBytes());
            out.flush();
            byte[] b = new byte[512];
            while (in.read(b) != -1) {
                System.out.print(new String(b));
            }
            telnet.disconnect();
        } catch (IOException e) {
            e.printStackTrace();
        }
    }
}
```
<<<explanation>>>: This code connects to a server on the specified port, sends the "ls" command, and then reads the server's response. The response is printed to the console. The TelnetClient class is part of the commons-net library, which you mentioned you were considering.
